[normal]The Additional Written Evidence is a submission by the author in his personal capacity. The Additional 
[normal]Evidence presents examination of the 
[normal]Worst Case Accident Scenario of bus full of school children being struck by a
[normal] high speed train at an Automatic Half Barrier Crossing
[normal].  
[normal]The Case study shows that the societal risk resulting from a hazardous event of a train crash into bus carrying passenger
[normal](s) or workers at Automatic Half Barrier or Full Barrier Crossings or Unmanned Private Crossings are real and fall into intolerable zone. 
[normal]This submission is to be read together with the earlier 
[normal]Additional Written Evidence and 
[normal]Written Evidence SLC 015. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Author is British Naturalised citizen since 2006. 
[normal]Author‘s experience in system safety engineering research and experience is evidenced by the publications of peer reviewed publications at the Institute of Engineers and Technology ( IE
[normal]T) International System Safety Conf
[normal]erences in 2006, 2010, 2011, 2012 and 2013. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Author was employed at RSSB from 2004 till 2010 as a System Engineer and deployed the System for Railway Investigations Methodology at RSSB
[normal] for identifying hazards and analysing risks of few signalling systems
[normal]. This methodology showed that RSSB Safety Risk Assessment 
[normal]and Decision Making Process 
[normal]suffer from 
[normal]what is known as Group-think bias
[normal]. 
[normal]This finding was shared with the community of 
[normal]railwa
[normal]y 
[normal]engineers at the IET System Safety Conference October 2010. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Author was awarded a Letter of Gratitude by the IET in 2009 for his contribution to the UK HSE Consultation Document,’’ Be Part of Solution, the UK HSE’s Strategy for the 21st
[normal] Century’’. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This paper presents
[normal] the results of analysis of 
[normal]specific type 
[normal]of 
[normal]l
[normal]evel crossing acc
[normal]ident 
[normal]using 
[normal]the System for Railway Investigations Methodology (SIRI)
[normal]. An unpublished paper by author explored the risks of a bus-train 
[normal]collision and established the fact operating in knowledge based behaviour using the widely accepted Skill-Rules-Knowledge Framework will lead to a 
[normal]fata
[normal] bus and train collision due to the lack of effective measures to prevent such an occurrence
[normal] (Appicharla,
[normal] 2009)
[normal]. 
[normal]In this 
[normal]latest 
[normal]application, the
[normal] SIRI Methodology explores two
[normal] kinds of in
[normal]terfaces. First, 
[normal]interfaces between the hazard (release event of uncontrolled energy), the victims and the system of barriers and controls to prevent the uncontrolled energy
[normal] f
[normal]rom harming the victims. Second, interfaces between information item available from historical accident data and using Bayesian approach to risk assessment for updating the information item to verify biases inherent in subject matter experts risk analysis
[normal].
[normal] Examination of these interfaces 
[normal]by the analyst 
[normal]presents a complete picture of human latent and active errors. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The aim of the study is to produce a
[normal] comprehensive 
[normal]discussion of factors that can contribute to a 
[normal]potential sever
[normal]e
[normal] accident as 
[normal]using the public
[normal]ly available data. The study results are submitted to the Transport Select Committee to inform their decision making
[normal] process 
[normal]on the theme of Safety at Level Crossings. 
[normal]&#xa0;
