[normal]Illusion of understanding is a term borrowed from Nobel Laureate, Daniel 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] (Kahneman, 2011)
[normal]. The illusion of understanding is graphically illustrated in the enigmatic picture shown on the next page. 
[normal]Our perceptions are not stable can be learnt from the double perception resulting from viewing the picture of a woman in the Figure
[normal] 1. This can be treated as a case in epistemic blindness. 
[normal]The case of double perception is an active subjective of research for psychologists. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]An
[normal]other
[normal] example of epistemic blindness is the legal case of Essex Level crossing Accident. Judge Turner accuse
[normal]d Network Rail of "corporate blindness". He said: "The Company unreservedly apologises for its failures which contributed to the deaths of these young girls." Network Rail, in part by itself and in part through its predecessor 
[normal]Railtrack
[normal], failed to ensure t
[normal]hat the risks were properly assessed, controlled or managed." 
[normal] 
[normal]The company concedes that the procedures or standards in place for conducting level crossing risk assessments before 2005 were deficient." (BBC News 2012)
[normal] (Appicharla, 2012)
[normal].
