[normal]Nobel Laurea
[normal]te Daniel 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] cautioned 
[normal]against blaming experts for their failing to forecast accurately in an unpredictable world (pp241)
[normal] (Kahneman, 2011)
[normal].  As per Daniel 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] claims for correct intuitions in an unpredicta
[normal]ble situation are self-delusional at best, sometimes worse. In the absence of valid- cues, intuitive “hits” are due to either luck or to lies. The rule to remember is that intuition cannot be trusted in the absence of stable regularities in the environment
[normal]. Author notes that this rule applies to author as well as 
[normal]a 
[normal]railway firm’s executives.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Arthur Schopenhauer noted in the early 19
[normal]th
[normal] century, that firms have a tendency of issuing bank notes without making adequate capital provision(pp123)
[normal] (Schopenhaeur,
[normal] 1813/2006)
[normal]. This tendency is still prevalent among firms in the 21
[normal]st
[normal] century has become public knowledge in 2008. Arthur Schopenhauer argued that both David Hume and Immanuel Kant did not comprehend the phenomena of cau
[normal]sation correctly (pp106)
[normal] (Schopenhae
[normal]ur, 1813/2006)
[normal]. Nobel Laureate Bertrand Russell argued
[normal] 
[normal]Arthur Schopenhauer did not refute inductive hypothesis advanced by David Hume in his treatise of History of Western Philosophy
[normal] (Russell, 1945)
[normal].  
[normal]However, with the Bayesian approach to accident and risk analysis by advanced by 
[normal]Nobel Laureate Daniel
[normal] 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal], objection raised against Arthur Schopenhauer is no longer tenable. 
[normal]Nobel Laureate Daniel 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] draws our attention to the fact that an insti
[normal]tutional risk manager acting as an agent on behalf of an organisation has to note the decision dilemma between intensely loss-averse moral attitudes and efficient risk management has no simple 
[normal]and 
[normal]compelling solution (
[normal]pp342).  However, GB Rail industry exe
[normal]cutives behave as if 
[normal]they have a simple and compelling solution to the problem of harm arising at level crossings: educate 
[normal]and enforce rules and regulations on 
[normal]the public. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Roger Ford echoes author’s sentiments. 
[normal]Roger Ford writes in the latest issue of Modern Railways that the past president of IRSE, Francis How, explained 
[normal]why concept of “safety” went missing 
[normal]  
[normal]from the Rail Technical Strategy Leadership’s document. Because Britain’s railways are among the safest 
[normal]in Europe and while it I always important to look for ways of improving safety that it is not our most important priority in terms of achieving a major improvement
[normal] (Ford, November, 2013)
[normal]. 
[normal]Roger Ford’s solution is to set up a new discipline called Transitio
[normal]n Safety Management to deal with changes and how to maintain safety during those changes so that we do not lose safety on the way.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Risk assessor
[normal]s and electronic 
[normal]engineers’
[normal] constant refrain is that o
[normal]f inherent uncertainty at the atomic level of matter.  
[normal]Let us consider their objection. 
[normal]Atomic physicists are aware of the striking feature of the unstable particles in the atomic world is their stability. No excited state of atom is truly discrete, stationary and permanent. For example, an electron orbiting B
[normal]ohr’s orbit during a time period of 10
[normal]-15 
[normal]seconds lives in that state for a period of 10
[normal]-8 
[normal]seconds. During this period 
[normal]of 10
[normal]-8 
[normal]seconds, an electron goes through 
[normal]some 
[normal]10
[normal]7 
[normal]oscillations
[normal] (pp46)
[normal] (Merzbacher, 1961)
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, if we extend the 
[normal]Nobel Laureate’s 
