[normal]If we assume that the above data is po
[normal]ssessed of some kind of 
[normal]central 
[normal]tendency then it is 
[normal]possible
[normal] to work out 
[normal]the mea
[normal]n rate of fatalities and
[normal] the confidence interval for the given data set.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The following definition
[normal] of Confidence Interval is taken from the Microsoft Excel package licensed to use by Microsoft to the author. 
[normal]Books on Statistics can also be consulted for verification. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The confidence interval is a range of values. Your sample mean, x, is at the centre 
[normal]of this range and the range is x ± CONFIDENCE.NORM. For example, if x is the sample mean of delivery times for products ordered through the mail, x ± CONFIDENCE.NORM is a range of population means. For any population mean, μ0, in this range, the probabilit
[normal]y of obtaining a sample mean further from μ0 than x is greater than alpha; for any population mean, μ0, not in this range, the probability of obtaining a sample mean further from μ0 than x is less than alpha. In other words, assume that we use x, 
[normal]standard_
[normal]dev
[normal], and size to construct a two-tailed test at significance level alpha of the hypothesis that the population mean is μ0. Then we will not
[normal] 
[normal]reject 
[normal]that
[normal] hypothesis if μ0 is in the confidence interval and will reject that hypothesis if μ0 is not in the confidence interval. The confidence interval does not allow us to infer that there is probability 1 – alpha that our next package will take a delivery time 
[normal]that is in the confidence interval.
[normal] 
[normal]Therefore, based upon the alpha of .05 and a three sigma deviation, the confidence interval for the data set of fatalities is computed to 
[normal]a mean value of 
[normal]17.78 ± 1.75978
[normal]. 
[normal]However, 
[normal]we find that range of 
[normal]fatalities
[normal] o
[normal]bserve
[normal]d fall outside this range
[normal]. Therefore, the thesis of 3 sigma deviation is not true. We must seek an alternate figure to satisfy the dispersion in the data. Based
[normal] u
[normal]pon the alpha of .05 and 
[normal]80
[normal] sigma deviation, the confidence interval for the data set of fatal
[normal]ities
[normal] is worked out to a mean value of 
[normal]17.78±
[normal]31.35
[normal]. 
[normal]Author is unable to comprehend how 
[normal]any risk assessor 
[normal]can
[normal] find any 
[normal]meaningful 
[normal]pattern 
[normal]of risk 
[normal]from such widely dispersed data of fatalities. 
