[normal]The application of 
[normal]Bayes
[normal] Rules is argued by Nobel Laureate, Daniel 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] is chapter 16 of his treatise
[normal] on human thinking (pp166-167)
[normal] (Kahneman, 2011)
[normal].  The case 
[normal]scenario
[normal] involves a hit-r
[normal]un accident in the night. First, information item is that there are 85% of the cabs operating in the city of Blue colour. The second information item is that eye witness identified the car as blue one. The third information item is that the witness reliabi
[normal]lity in successfully identifying the two colours is 80% of the time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Box 1 below is an application of 
[normal]Bayes’s
[normal] rule to infer the changes in the 
[normal]environment
[normal]. This example is drawn from the medical science paper published in Nature magazine in 2009
[normal] (The
[normal]odore J Perkins, 2009)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The prior probability of an un-observed random variable X, based upon the another random variable say Y is observed
[normal] can be computed using the Bayesian rule
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In the case of hit and run scenario, the variable X takes a value of 0.15 
[normal]based upon the prior probability. Given the fact that an eye witness account has observed a blue colour, and the reliability of the eye witness to be 80%, we can update our prior pro
[normal]bability information in the following way. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The visualisation of the above relation between two random variables X and Y is shown in Figure 
[normal]3
[normal].
[normal] This depicts the four –fold pattern suggested by 
[normal]Nobel Laureate Daniel
[normal] 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal](pp 310-333)
[normal] (Kahneman, 2011)
[normal]. Au
[normal]thor 
[normal]as noted the 
[normal]Nobel Laureate Daniel
[normal] 
[normal]Kahneman
[normal] insight that decision weights that people assign to outcomes are not identical to the probabilities of these outcomes. This insight was revealed 
[normal]in form of 
[normal]the subjective biases on the part of 
[normal]members of 
[normal]Jap
[normal]anese civil engineering society and executives of 
[normal]nuclear
[normal] plant operator, supplier and other agencies whose actions contributed to the Japanese Nuclear Accident studied by author
[normal] (Appicharla, 2013)
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Figure 
[normal]3
[normal]: Diagram showing conditional probabilities between two random variables X and Y
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]P(X = 
[normal]Not Green /
[normal] Given Y) = P(Y
[normal]= 
[normal]Blue
[normal]/ X= 
[normal]Blue
[normal]) 
[normal]P(X= 
[normal]Blue
[normal]) /
[normal] 
[normal]P(Y= Blue). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The probability of P(Y= 
[normal]Blue
[normal])
[normal]= 
[normal]( Y = Not Green / X = Not Green)
[normal]* P(X = Not Green) 
[normal] +  P( Y = Not Green / X = Green)
[normal]* P( 
[normal] 
[normal]X = Green)
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]       = .15*.8 +.85*.2
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]       = .29
[normal]P( Y = Not Green / X = Not Green)
[normal]*
[normal] 
[normal]P(X = Not Green)  
[normal] = .15*.8 =.12
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Therefore, 
[normal]P(X = Not Green / Given Y= Blue) = .12/.29 = .0041 = 41%. This 
[normal]result 
[normal]is different 
[normal]from 15% base rate information as well as 80% of the eye witness reliability
[normal] available to us to form a risk judgement on the road accident. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Similarly, in
[normal] the 
[normal]case of level crossing accident, railway firm’s world-wide informs
[normal] us that 90% of the times, the
[normal] system of barriers and co
[normal]ntrols were ON
[normal] 
[normal]ie
[normal] they were closed
[normal]. 
[normal]By this statement
[normal] it
[normal] is meant that the user of level crossing is presented with adequate audio-visual warning of impending danger in the form of a train. 
[normal]This may be called as the variable X. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Eye witness accoun
[normal]ts inform us that bus driver 
[normal]ran past the closed barriers. Assuming that the eye witness reliability is 90%, we can update our prior information 
[normal]in 
[normal]following
[normal] way 
[normal]using the
[normal] above examples. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]P( X = Barriers 
[normal] 
[normal]ON
[normal]) 
